      "id": 1,
      "text": "Boston was founded on Shawmut Peninsula in 1630 by English Puritan settlers, named after Boston, Lincolnshire.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The first European to live in what would become Boston was William Blaxton, a Cambridge-educated Anglican cleric.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        10
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "In 1635, America’s first public school, Boston Latin School, opened its doors in Boston.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        11
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Boston Public Library, founded in 1852, was the first free library in the United States.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        6
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Logan International Airport, located in East Boston, serves as the city’s principal airport.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boston"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Bluebikes, Boston’s bikeshare program that began as Hubway in 2011, now offers a dense network of bikes across the city.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
